how do proctoring platforms typically detect cheating in online exams? What technologies 
do they use to monitor users?"

Proctoring platforms use a multi-layered approach combining computer vision, biometrics, and environmental analysis to detect suspicious behavior during online exams. Here's how the major technologies work:
Core Detection Methods
1. Identity Verification
 
Government ID scanning with OCR to match names and photos
 
Facial recognition comparing live video to ID photos
 
Biometric voiceprints for audio verification in some platforms
2. Visual Monitoring (Computer Vision)
 
Eye tracking/gaze detection to identify if you're looking off-screen repeatedly
 
Head pose estimation to detect unusual angles or looking away from the camera
 
Multiple face detection to spot a second person entering the room
 
Object detection for unauthorized materials (phones, textbooks, notes)
 
Virtual machine detection by analyzing screen resolution, mouse behavior, and system fingerprints
3. Audio Analysis
 
Voice activity detection to flag when someone speaks
 
Acoustic fingerprinting to identify if exam content is being read aloud
 
Background noise classification to detect whispering or typing on a secondary device
4. Browser & System Monitoring
 
Lockdown browsers that restrict access to other tabs, applications, or copy-paste functions
 
Keystroke dynamics analyzing typing rhythm (though this is less common due to privacy concerns)
 
Screen recording and secondary camera requirements (showing desk/room)
 
Process monitoring to detect remote desktop tools or virtualization software
5. Behavioral Analytics
 
Anomaly detection algorithms flagging unusual patterns (e.g., completing a complex exam too quickly, long pauses followed by rapid answering)
 
Mouse movement analysis for robotic or scripted behavior
 
IP geolocation and device fingerprinting to prevent proxy test-taking
How They Typically Respond to Flags
Most platforms don't auto-fail students. Instead, they:
 
Generate timestamped incident reports with video clips for instructors
 
Use AI confidence scoring (low/medium/high risk) to prioritize human review
 
Provide live proctors (in hybrid models) who can intervene in real-time via chat
Privacy & Technical Limitations
 
False positives are common: eye trackers may flag students with vision disabilities, ADHD-related movement, or simply thinking while looking away
 
Privacy concerns have led to restrictions in some jurisdictions (e.g., EU GDPR considerations, Illinois BIPA for biometrics)
 
Workarounds exist but carry significant risk: virtual machines, HDMI splitters, hidden earpieces, or proxy test-takers are detectable by advanced systems
Major Platform Examples
 
Proctorio: Browser lockdown + AI monitoring
 
Examity: Live proctors + AI hybrid
 
Respondus Monitor: Automated video analysis
 
ProctorU: Live proctoring with full environment scans
The field is rapidly evolving—some platforms are now experimenting with keyboard acoustic analysis (detecting if you're typing on a hidden device) and pupil dilation tracking (stress indicators), though these remain controversial.
If you're asking from an institutional or educator perspective, the most effective approach is usually a hybrid model: AI for scalable flagging plus human review for context, combined with clear policies about what is and isn't permitted. If you're asking as a test-taker, the safest path is understanding your specific platform's rules thoroughly, as capabilities vary significantly.

